# Git Quick Revision (Interview and Exam)

Fast, high-value Git reference with top commands and common real-world scenarios.

## A) Top 30 Commands You Should Know

| Command | Purpose | Typical use |
|---|---|---|
| `git init` | Initialize local repository. | Start a new project with Git. |
| `git clone <url>` | Copy remote repository locally. | Begin working on an existing project. |
| `git status` | Show changed/staged/untracked files. | Check current state before actions. |
| `git add <file>` | Stage one file. | Commit selected changes only. |
| `git add .` | Stage all changes. | Commit all current local work. |
| `git commit -m "msg"` | Create commit with message. | Save logical chunk of work. |
| `git commit --amend` | Edit latest commit. | Fix last message or missed file. |
| `git log --oneline --graph --decorate --all -n 20` | Compact graph history. | Understand branch/merge flow quickly. |
| `git diff` | Show unstaged changes. | Review edits before staging. |
| `git diff --staged` | Show staged changes. | Verify what will be committed. |
| `git branch` | List branches. | See available local branches. |
| `git switch <branch>` | Switch to existing branch. | Move between tasks. |
| `git switch -c <branch>` | Create and switch branch. | Start a new feature branch. |
| `git merge <branch>` | Merge target branch into current. | Integrate work from another branch. |
| `git rebase origin/main` | Replay commits on latest main. | Keep feature branch linear. |
| `git rebase --continue` | Continue rebase after conflict fix. | Finish interrupted rebase. |
| `git rebase --abort` | Cancel rebase operation. | Rebase went wrong. |
| `git pull origin main` | Fetch + merge main. | Sync local branch with remote main. |
| `git fetch origin` | Download refs only. | Check remote updates safely first. |
| `git push origin main` | Push local main commits. | Publish latest main changes. |
| `git push -u origin <branch>` | Push and set upstream. | First push of a new branch. |
| `git remote -v` | Show remotes and URLs. | Verify repository endpoint. |
| `git remote set-url origin <url>` | Change origin URL. | Move repo to new owner/server. |
| `git stash` | Temporarily shelve changes. | Urgent branch switch. |
| `git stash pop` | Restore latest stash and remove. | Continue shelved work. |
| `git restore --staged <file>` | Unstage file. | Staged by mistake. |
| `git restore <file>` | Discard unstaged file edits. | Revert local accidental edit. |
| `git reflog` | Show HEAD movement history. | Recover lost commits/branch tips. |
| `git reset --soft HEAD~1` | Undo commit, keep staged changes. | Rewrite last commit cleanly. |
| `git reset --hard HEAD~1` | Undo commit and discard local changes. | Last resort cleanup (dangerous). |

## B) Most Asked Practical Scenarios

### 1) "origin already exists" while adding remote

```bash
git remote -v
git remote set-url origin https://github.com/harishmsgit/Container-Orchestration-Scaling.git
git remote -v
```

Use when:
- Remote is already configured but points to wrong URL.

### 2) Create feature branch and push first time

```bash
git switch -c feature/login-rate-limit
git add .
git commit -m "feat: add login rate limiter"
git push -u origin feature/login-rate-limit
```

Use when:
- Starting a new task and publishing branch for PR.

### 3) Bring latest main into your feature branch

Merge approach:
```bash
git switch main
git pull origin main
git switch feature/login-rate-limit
git merge main
```

Rebase approach:
```bash
git switch feature/login-rate-limit
git fetch origin
git rebase origin/main
```

Use when:
- Main has moved ahead and you need current codebase.

### 4) Accidentally committed on main

```bash
git switch -c feature/move-main-commit
git switch main
git reset --hard HEAD~1
git switch feature/move-main-commit
```

Use when:
- Commit should have gone to feature branch, not main.

### 5) Undo last commit but keep code

```bash
git reset --soft HEAD~1
```

Use when:
- Commit message/content needs correction before pushing.

### 6) Recover lost commit using reflog

```bash
git reflog
git checkout <lost-commit-hash>
git switch -c recovery-branch
```

Use when:
- Commit seems missing after reset/rebase.

### 7) Save temporary work and switch urgently

```bash
git stash push -m "wip: stream buffering fix"
git switch main
# do urgent work
git switch feature/stream-fix
git stash pop
```

Use when:
- Mid-work interruption requires immediate context switch.

### 8) Clean untracked generated files

```bash
git clean -fd
```

Use when:
- Build/temp files clutter workspace.

## C) Fast Interview Notes

- `merge` keeps branch history with explicit merge commit.
- `rebase` rewrites commit base for linear history.
- `fetch` is safe sync (download only), `pull` is fetch + integrate.
- `reflog` is your best recovery tool after mistakes.
- Avoid `reset --hard` unless you are 100 percent sure.

## D) Minimal Daily Workflow

```bash
git status
git switch -c feature/my-task
git add .
git commit -m "feat: implement my task"
git fetch origin
git rebase origin/main
git push -u origin feature/my-task
```

